children.subject: I think your coding skills develop as you take more upper divs and you seem to have barely taken any. Long way to go..

history.content:
Just my personal experience, but 184 was my first upper div CS class (alongside 170) and I think it set me up really well to handle future programming projects. 

I think the follow up below is correct that in general any upper div CS class will continue to help your programming skills/experience, but it's probably fair to say that 184's projects are larger than at least some/most CS upper divs, so it's probably a good fit for your goals.

Haven't taken 169, so can't comment on that.

children.subject:
61c was also a major development because we were working with very different concepts than 61ab. In 61ab, it was like "come up with a clever python trick to solve a fun Towers of Hanoi Problem" while like the 61c projects require you to have a deep understand of the concepts such as C, memory management, processors, caching in order to implement the projects fully. 

While the topics of the projects may not prepare your for cs research (if you aren't doing like lower level stuff), you really flex your problem solving and debugging skills in my opinion. 

One of the projects is where you build a fully functioning 2 stage pipelined CPU processor in logisim, and while you probably won't use logisim after this class, the project was a huge understanding of how to take theoretical concepts and actually build them by hand. It was a rough project but I felt so accomplished after and it looks heckin cool.

history.content:
I am interested in CS research, and want to get better at writing programs to improve my ability to implement papers and iterate potential research ideas. Although I enjoyed 61AB and 188, I didn't feel that they made me a strong programmer, especially as many of the programs had a lot of starter code.

I've heard 184 is project heavy; how useful is 184 for my case (I am also interested in the course material)? Should I take CS 169 as well?
history.subject: Is CS 184 effective for improving programming skills?
